  <span id="freeText13523213008731915748" style="display:none">Year of Wonders, Geraldine Brooks 2001 novel describes the plague years of 1666 and concludes with a very unusual and somewhat unbalanced ending. <br><br>While reading I thought of Arthur Miller’s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17250.The_Crucible" title="The Crucible by Arthur Miller" rel="nofollow noopener">The Crucible</a> and of course Camus’ <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11989.The_Plague" title="The Plague by Albert Camus" rel="nofollow noopener">The Plague</a> (and I forgive her much about the ending for the mention of Oran which could NOT have been coincidence). <br><br>This is simply, elegantly written and yet the force and brutality of the plot, told in such straightforward prose is also reminiscent of Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God (another obvious and brilliant reference) – relentless and shocking.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1560825953i/27684837.jpg" width="400" height="400" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
