        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2657150221" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13765876240823337318">The bubonic plague hit Eyam, England in the 1600’s like the apocalypse. Geraldine Brooks writes a grim tale based on a true incident in which this village is nearly annihilated and causes its residents to question God’s existence, God’s ability to intervene, and the power of nature. The strength of women, the hysteria of witchcraft, natural herbal cures, and the ignorance of staunching the spread of disease unfold in this tragedy. <br/><br/>I enjoyed reading this well written portrayal of life in Britain </span>
  <span id="freeText13765876240823337318" style="display:none">The bubonic plague hit Eyam, England in the 1600’s like the apocalypse. Geraldine Brooks writes a grim tale based on a true incident in which this village is nearly annihilated and causes its residents to question God’s existence, God’s ability to intervene, and the power of nature. The strength of women, the hysteria of witchcraft, natural herbal cures, and the ignorance of staunching the spread of disease unfold in this tragedy. <br /><br />I enjoyed reading this well written portrayal of life in Britain in the Restoration period, even with the reveal at the end that seems highly improbable. </span>
